0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">What give=
s?</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px=
;font-size: 16px;">The last time most people in tech heard about Oracle was=
 when they sued Google over the Java API in 2010, which eventually led to a=
 US Supreme Court decision which determined that implementing an API consti=
tutes fair use.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line=
-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">This kind of jockeying over IP, especially =
in the mid-2010&#8217;s when open source, open standards, and open platform=
s were all the rage, cemented Oracle&#8217;s (not entirely undeserved) repu=
tation as a company more interested in litigation and vendor lock-in than i=
nnovation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-heig=
ht: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Indeed, by the 2010&#8217;s Oracle looked to be =
losing. After leading the way in enterprise databases and integrated softwa=
re for years, competing fiercely for market share, Oracle missed three succ=
essive waves in computing: the internet, mobile, and finally, the cloud.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font=
-size: 16px;"><span>While Oracle was able to continue earning money from it=
s extensive enterprise and government contracts which were locked in for ye=
ars, and was able to hang on to relevance by using its distributional advan=
tage with its existing customers to ship Oracle versions of emerging platfo=
rms and software, by 2016 things</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redi=
rect/97c1f2f6-6d58-4317-b9ce-9b7ec9e7afd0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);t=
ext-decoration: underline;"> looked pretty grim</a><span>. Oracle had ceded=
 much of cloud to AWS, and Microsoft had started to muscle in with its own =
customer relationships to Fortune 500s and governments.</span></p><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16=
px;">While still a titan, Oracle&#8217;s lack of innovation seemed to predi=
ct a steady slide into irrelevance. Yet over the last few years, the compan=
y has made a stunning comeback, somehow indispensable to the biggest player=
s.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px=
;font-size: 16px;"><span>The straightforward business reason is that Oracle=
 effectively positioned itself through massive investment in GPU datacenter=
s to become one of the go-to players for training large language models, es=
pecially among its government and large enterprise customer base. The early=
 miss on cloud also turned out to be an advantage, as AWS, Microsoft, and G=
oogle chose Oracle as a neutral service provider to help run their AI-focus=
ed datacenters.</span><span class=3D"footnote-anchor-email" data-component-=
name=3D"FootnoteAnchorToDOMStatic" style=3D"font-size: 20px;">&#179;</span>=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;f=
ont-size: 16px;">Given the enormous investments in AI being made across the=
 board, Oracle&#8217;s positioning has allowed it to capture a lot of value=
 doing what it does best; large, long-term sales and services contracts wit=
h big players. The 90&#8217;s are back.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;c=
olor: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">But the straightfor=
ward business reason is narratively boring. Instead, it&#8217;s much more i=
nteresting to understand Oracle as an extension of Larry Ellison&#8217;s wi=
ll.</p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px;line-height: 26px;"><hr style=3D"margi=
n: 32px 0;padding: 0;height: 1px;background: #e6e6e6;border: none;"></div><=
p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-s=
ize: 16px;">So who is Larry Ellison? Despite increasing public interest (fo=
r various reasons) in the emerging class of powerful tech billionaires, Law=
rence Joseph Ellison seems to remain relatively quiet. Reportedly a close f=
riend and mentor to Elon Musk, the 80 year old Ellison has led a colorful l=
ife, though has lately stayed out of the media spotlight.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><=
span>To the extent that Oracle is an extension of Ellison&#8217;s will, Ora=
cle&#8217;s fortunes reflect his leadership. My favorite history of the com=
pany, &#8220;</span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/346592a9-8=
a71-4560-a4db-cb858ad85ddb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);text-decoration:=
 underline;">Softwar</a></em><span>&#8221;, gives the impression that the l=
ifecycle of Oracle has gone as follows:</span></p><ol style=3D"margin-top: =
0;padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-=
left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">Larry Ellison has an insight which le=
ads to a breakthrough initiative which has the potential to reposition Orac=
le to the forefront of the industry, completely bypassing the competition.<=
/p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55=
);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4=
px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">It works.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0=
 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom:=
 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">Lar=
ry Ellison checks out to go sailing or play tennis or something for like a =
year.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-l=
eft: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><span>Oracle gets into trouble. New en=
trants and existing competitors are eating away at its market share, and Or=
acle is losing head-to-head.</span><span class=3D"footnote-anchor-email" da=
ta-component-name=3D"FootnoteAnchorToDOMStatic" style=3D"font-size: 20px;">=
&#8308;</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;=
padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">GOTO 1.</p></li></ol><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16=
px;">For example, in the early 90s, Oracle faced stiff competition from sev=
eral fast-growing software companies. At the time, enterprise software was =
heavily customized by the end-user, and third party integrators who would m=
unge together several &#8216;best of breed&#8217; packages to create franke=
nstinian hodge-podges of software, one solution per organizational function=
 or process. It was a nightmare for everyone but the vendors and integrator=
s, who made money either way.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(=
54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Rather than competing o=
n features, or cost, or attempting to create more best-of-breed products, o=
r pay ever fatter sales commissions which ate away margins, Ellison chose t=
o tell his customers that they were </span><strong>doing it wrong</strong><=
span>.</span><span class=3D"footnote-anchor-email" data-component-name=3D"F=
ootnoteAnchorToDOMStatic" style=3D"font-size: 20px;">&#8309;</span><span> S=
oftware shouldn&#8217;t be built to fit business processes, he said, busine=
ss processes must adapt to software. Vertically integrated </span><em>platf=
orms</em><span> were the future.</span><span class=3D"footnote-anchor-email=
" data-component-name=3D"FootnoteAnchorToDOMStatic" style=3D"font-size: 20p=
x;">&#8310;</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);l=
ine-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Getting everything from one vendor=
 meant you didn&#8217;t need customization or integration, things would jus=
t work. Yes, it meant changing the way you were used to doing things, but t=
hat&#8217;s what it took to get the most out of software. It just so happen=
ed that the vendor investing the most into this vertical strategy was Oracl=
e. The move to vertically integrated platforms locked in Oracle&#8217;s dis=
tributional advantage for another decade.</span><span class=3D"footnote-anc=
hor-email" data-component-name=3D"FootnoteAnchorToDOMStatic" style=3D"font-=
size: 20px;">&#8311;</span><span> Between 1990 and 2001, Oracle&#8217;s rev=
enue went from $196M to $10 billion.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Tacking b=
efore competitors may have come naturally to Ellison, a lifelong sailing en=
thusiast. In the 2010 America&#8217;s Cup, Oracle-sponsored </span><em>USA-=
17</em><span> defeated Swiss </span><em>Alinghi 5.</em><span> This gave the=
 winning team the right to decide the class of boat for the 2013. Making an=
 already expensive and dangerous sport far more expensive, and far more dan=
gerous, Team Oracle chose wingsail catamarans, with hydrofoils.</span></p><=
p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-s=
ize: 16px;"><span>These boats could literally sail faster than the wind. Th=
e change was far from incremental; sailing teams were pushed to their absol=
ute limit in terms of cost and training. A crew member from Artemis Racing =
